4. Implementation Approach
4.1 Controller Layer (New)

Create Spring Boot 3.x controllers to replace CXF endpoints.

Controllers will:

Accept JSON payloads.

Use existing POJOs from the service layer directly as @RequestBody and @ResponseBody.

Call existing service methods directly (same as SOAP used to do).

Example:

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/customers")
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class CustomerController {

    private final CustomerService customerService;

    @PostMapping("/create")
    public ResponseEntity<CustomerResponse> createCustomer(
            @RequestBody CustomerRequest request) {
        CustomerResponse response = customerService.createCustomer(request);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(response);
    }
}

4.2 Reuse of Existing POJOs

The existing JAXB-annotated request and response classes (used by CXF) can be reused with minimal modification.

Before (SOAP/JAXB class):

@XmlRootElement(name = "CustomerRequest")
@XmlAccessorType(XmlAccessType.FIELD)
public class CustomerRequest {
    private String customerId;
    private String name;
}


After (REST/JSON compatible class):

@Data
@JsonInclude(JsonInclude.Include.NON_NULL)
public class CustomerRequest {
    @JsonProperty("customerId")
    private String customerId;

    @JsonProperty("name")
    private String name;
}


➡️ You can retain JAXB annotations; Jackson ignores them by default.
If needed, you can add minimal @JsonProperty for name alignment with JSON spec.

4.3 JSON Serialization

Library: Jackson (included in Spring Boot by default).

No need for JAXB converters.

Configure Jackson globally:

spring:
  jackson:
    serialization:
      indent_output: true
    property-naming-strategy: SNAKE_CASE


Use @JsonInclude and @JsonIgnore to control response visibility.

4.4 Exception Handling

Implement a global exception handler to replace SOAPFaults with structured JSON responses.

Example:

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    @ExceptionHandler(ServiceException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleServiceError(ServiceException ex) {
        ErrorResponse error = new ErrorResponse("SERVICE_ERROR", ex.getMessage());
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.BAD_REQUEST).body(error);
    }

    @ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponse> handleGenericError(Exception ex) {
        ErrorResponse error = new ErrorResponse("GENERIC_ERROR", ex.getMessage());
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR).body(error);
    }
}


ErrorResponse model:

@Data
@AllArgsConstructor
@NoArgsConstructor
public class ErrorResponse {
    private String code;
    private String message;
    private Instant timestamp = Instant.now();
}

4.5 EOD Handling with Kafka

To manage EOD switch events across stateless pods:

Introduce a Kafka topic (e.g., eod-switch).

The EOD trigger (from App1 or App2) sends a message to this topic.

All pods listen to the topic and update their runtime state (e.g., DB URL switch).

Example:

@Component
@Slf4j
public class EodEventListener {

    @KafkaListener(topics = "eod-switch")
    public void onEodEvent(String message) {
        log.info("EOD switch triggered: {}", message);
        // Switch DB configuration here
    }
}

5. Advantages of Reusing Service-Layer POJOs
Benefit	Description
Minimal Regression	The same business/service logic continues to function identically.
No Mapping Overhead	Directly use existing POJOs instead of introducing DTO mapping frameworks.
Reduced Latency	Avoid SOAP serialization/deserialization layers.
Simplified Maintenance	Fewer moving parts (no generated stubs, no adapters).
Easier Testing	Controller → Service testing straightforward using JUnit and MockMVC.
6. When to Introduce DTO Mapping Later

Introduce dedicated REST DTOs (and possibly MapStruct) only if:

App2’s JSON contract differs significantly from existing service models.

Sensitive or internal fields must be hidden from API responses.

You plan to expose APIs externally through Apigee or other gateways.

In such cases, you’ll:

Keep service-layer objects unchanged.

Add lightweight DTOs for REST exposure.

Introduce MapStruct for compile-time-safe conversions.

